{"title_page": "Asher Fisch", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli conductor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name =Asher Fisch\n| image = Asher Fisch.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =1958\n| birth_place = [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality = Israeli\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education =\n| employer = \n| occupation =conductor, pianist\n| title = \n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n| box_width = \n}}\n'''Asher Fisch''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: \u05d0\u05e9\u05e8 \u05e4\u05d9\u05e9) (born May 19, 1958, [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]) is an [[Israel]]i [[conductor (music)|conductor]] and [[pianist]].\n\nFisch began his career as an assistant of [[Daniel Barenboim]] and an associate conductor of the [[Berlin State Opera]]. He made his [[United States]] debut in 1995, conducting ''[[Der fliegende Holl\u00e4nder]]'' at the [[Los Angeles Opera]]. He was chief conductor of the [[Vienna]] ''[[Volksoper]]'' from 1995 to 2000. He served as music director of Israeli Opera from 1998 to 2008. [[Seattle Opera]] named him its principal guest conductor in October 2007.<ref>{{cite news | author=Matthew Westphal | title=Seattle Opera Appoints Asher Fisch Principal Guest Conductor | url=http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/7214.html | work=Playbill Arts | date=2007-10-16 | accessdate=2012-05-13}}</ref>\n\nFisch first guest-conducted the [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]] (WASO) in 1999. In May 2012, WASO announced the appointment of Fisch as its next principal conductor, effective 1 January 2014, with an initial contract of 3 years.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.waso.com.au/res/Media%20releases/MEDIA%20RELEASE%20WASO%20Principal%20Conductor%20announcement.pdf | title=WASO announces Principal Conductor and Artistic Adviser | publisher=West Australian Symphony Orchestra | date=3 May 2012 | accessdate=2012-05-06 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421101905/http://www.waso.com.au/res/Media%20releases/MEDIA%20RELEASE%20WASO%20Principal%20Conductor%20announcement.pdf | archive-date=21 April 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>  In September 2015, the WASO announced the extension of Fisch's contract until the end of 2019.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://d35ivtiultdflj.cloudfront.net/res/Media%20releases/MEDIA%20RELEASE%20WASO%202016%20season(1).pdf | title=WASO announces 2016 season and a renewed contract for Principal Conductor | publisher=West Australian Symphony Orchestra | date=2 September 2015 | accessdate=2017-07-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author=Stephen Bevis and Nevile Cohn | title=China beckons for WASO | url=https://thewest.com.au/entertainment/art/china-beckons-for-waso-ng-ya-128327 | work=The West Australian | date=2015-09-02 | accessdate=2017-07-04}}</ref> With the WASO, Fisch has recorded the symphonies of [[Brahms]].\n\n== Selected discography ==\n* Wagner - ''Der Ring Des Nibelungen''\n** State Opera of South Australia: Melba Recordings - ''Das Rheingold'' (MR301089-90), ''Die Walk\u00fcre'' (MR301091-94), ''Siegfried'' (MR301095-98), ''G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung'' (MR301099-102)\n** Seattle Opera: Avie AV2313\n* [[Gordon Getty]] - The Little Match Girl. [[Nikolai Schukoff]], [[Lester Lynch]], Melody Moore, Asher Fisch, Ulf Schirmer, [[Munich Radio Orchestra|M\u00fcnchner Rundfunkorchester]], Chor des Bayerischen Rundfunks. [[Pentatone (record label)|PENTATONE]] PTC 5186480 (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli conductor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name =Asher Fisch\n| image = Asher Fisch.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date =1958\n| birth_place = [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = \n| nationality = Israeli\n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education =\n| employer = \n| occupation =conductor, pianist\n| title = \n| salary = \n| networth = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n| box_width = \n}}\n'''Asher Fisch''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: \u05d0\u05e9\u05e8 \u05e4\u05d9\u05e9) (born May 19, 1958, [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]]) is an [[Israel]]i [[conductor (music)|conductor]] and [[pianist]].\n\nFisch began his career as an assistant of [[Daniel Barenboim]] and an associate conductor of the [[Berlin State Opera]]. He made his [[United States]] debut in 1995, conducting ''[[Der fliegende Holl\u00e4nder]]'' at the [[Los Angeles Opera]]. He was chief conductor of the [[Vienna]] ''[[Volksoper]]'' from 1995 to 2000. He served as music director of Israeli Opera from 1998 to 2008. [[Seattle Opera]] named him its principal guest conductor in October 2007.<ref>{{cite news | author=Matthew Westphal | title=Seattle Opera Appoints Asher Fisch Principal Guest Conductor | url=http://www.playbillarts.com/news/article/7214.html | work=Playbill Arts | date=2007-10-16 | accessdate=2012-05-13}}</ref>\n\nFisch first guest-conducted the [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]] (WASO) in 1999. In May 2012, WASO announced the appointment of Fisch as its next principal conductor, effective 1 January 2014, with an initial contract of 3 years.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.waso.com.au/res/Media%20releases/MEDIA%20RELEASE%20WASO%20Principal%20Conductor%20announcement.pdf | title=WASO announces Principal Conductor and Artistic Adviser | publisher=West Australian Symphony Orchestra | date=3 May 2012 | accessdate=2012-05-06 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421101905/http://www.waso.com.au/res/Media%20releases/MEDIA%20RELEASE%20WASO%20