{"title_page": "Moorefield GAA", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{more footnotes|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox GAA club\n| club gaa = Moorefield\n| crest = Moorefield_crest.jpg\n| irish = Achadh Mh\u00f3rdha\n| county = Kildare\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.172431|N|6.849471|W|region:IE_type:landmark|display=it}}\n| province = Leinster\n| nickname = The Moores \n| colours = Green and White\n| grounds = Moorefield GAA \n| founded = 1884\n| honours = \n| pattern_la = _white_hoops\n| pattern_b = _whiteV\n| pattern_ra = _white_hoops\n| leftarm = 008000\n| body = 008000\n| rightarm = 008000\n| shorts = FFFFFF\n| socks = 008000\n| f3 = 8\n| f2 = 2\n| f1 = 0\n| h3 = 3\n| h2 = 0\n| h1 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Moorefield''' is a [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] club in the parish of [[Newbridge, County Kildare|Newbridge]] [[County Kildare]], Ireland, winner of two Leinster Club Senior Football Championships, ten Senior County Football Championships and three Senior County Hurling Championships.\n\n==History==\nFolklore records that, in 1882, two brothers, John O'Kelly of Moorefield Road and James O'Kelly of Ballymany were instrumental in forming the first football team in [[Newbridge, County Kildare|Newbridge]]. Calling themselves the JJ O'Kellys they played matches against Mountrice, Eyrefield, Monasterevin, Kildare town and Milltown. In 1884, when the GAA was formed, the club changed its name from JJ O'Kelly's to Moorefield, the name of a townland in southern Newbridge.\n\n==Gaelic football==\nMoorefield beat Kilcullen in a one-sided county final in 1962, 2\u201311 to 0\u20132 to claim their first [[Kildare Senior Football Championship]] title. Carbury defeated Moorefield in the 1965 final.\n\nMoorefield re-emerged in the 1990s. A run of success that started with the minor championship of 1989(Under the name Pollardstown) and two more Leinster Leader Cups in 1994 and 1996 culminated in three successive finals 2000\u20132002, two of which were won. In 2000 Moorefield beat [[Kilcock GAA|Kilcock]] by 2\u201313 to 2\u20137 after goals from Cian O'Neill and gave them a 2\u201310 to 0\u20131 lead at half-time. Sarsfields overhauled Moorefield towards the end of the 2001 final in a closely contested decider to win 0\u201310 to 0\u20138. In 2002 Moorefield won their third title, beating near neighbours Sarsfields 1\u20138 to 0\u20136 thanks to a Ronan Sweeney penalty seconds into the second half. Moorefield were defeated in two Leinster club semi-final, by O'Hanrahan's 0\u201312 to 0\u201311 in 2000 and by Mattock Rangers by 3\u201313 to 2\u201310 in 2002.\n\nThe glory days of Moorefield, and indeed Newbridge football rose to a higher plane in 2006, when The Moors beat [[Allenwood GAA|Allenwood]] in the [[Kildare Senior Football Championship]] final, which lead on to a first [[Leinster Senior Club Football Championship]] victory for the town, beating Rhode of [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] on a wind-swept Sunday in December in the aptly named [[O'Moore Park]], [[County Laois]]. They were decisive victors, on a day that all present hoped would lead to a clear-cut rather than a marginal victory. It proved to be so, with a final score of 3 goals and 6 points (15 points) to 8 points for Rhode.\n\nThe club enjoys a particularly bittersweet rivalry with town neighbours Sarsfields, and as their respective fortunes rise and fall each side can be trusted to support the other, and indeed enjoy each other's fortune. In 2007 they won the [[Kildare Senior Football Championship]] for the second year running, beating Sarsfields.\n\nTheir football manager is Ross Glavin. In 2019 they were chasing an elusive three in a row senior championships, but as usual Sarsfields GAA stopped them achieving this feat.\n\nThe History of Moorefield gaa is well documented and can be viewed in two different documentaries about the club and its people, in \u2018Moorefield \u2018til I die\u2019 you can see how the hapless club run from one self destructive hazard to the next through mis-management and bad luck, in \u2018Benefits Street\u2019 you see how the club based in Pollardstown relies heavily on the riches of the nearby prosperous town of Newbridge, without these handouts Moorefield and its people would be considerably poor, ironically it is the riches of the better looking people from Sarsfields that keep this club in existence. Both documentaries show how Moorefield and its members are just extremely jealous of Athy gfc.\n\n==Hurling==\nMoorefield's 1\u201310 to 0\u20133 victory over Broadford in the 1963 county final bridged a twenty-year gap for Moorefield. Davey Dennis captained the team, Mick Leahy scored 0\u20137 of the total, Billy Quinn came on as substitute to score the goal, and Ned Goff, Jim Barker, Harry Fay, Colm Ruffley, Paddy Moore, Tom O'Connell and Stephen Schwer all collected medals as a result of the victory over a much-changed [[Broadford GAA|Broadford]] team. Moorefields most well-known hurler of all time would be Mick Maloney.{{fact|date=February 2017}}\n\nMoorefield won their third senior title in 1991 beating Coil Dubh in a replay, with the McMullen and Murray families making up six of the starting fifteen. Moorefield went on to represent Kildare in the Leinster Hurling Championship. They played Longford Slashers in the first round, which also went to a replay, then took on the mighty Birr in the next round.\n\nMoorefield won the replayed 2010 Intermediate Hurling Championship against Naas, 1\u201313 to 0\u201311 in Celbridge. The replay was an entertaining and hard-fought game between both sides at St. Conleths park ending on a score of 1\u201311 a piece, leaving the title to be decided for a later date. On the day Moorefield dominated the majority of the game, Moorefield led 0\u201310 0\u201307 at the interval. A goal from a 21-yard free in front of the goal by Gavin Sunderland put the Moores 6 points in front midway through the 2nd half. Moorefield defended like their life depended on it in the last few moments to keep a tremendous fight back from Naas from scoring any inspirational goals. Moorefield will now contest in the Senior ranks for 2011.\n\n==Titles won==\n* '''[[Leinster Senior Club Football Championship]]''' Winners 2006, 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hoganstand.com/Article/Index/279220 |title=Leinster club SFC final: Sweeney inspires remarkable Moorefield comeback  |accessdate=18 December 2017 |work=[[Hogan Stand]] |publisher= |date=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n* '''[[Leinster Senior Club Football Championship]]:''' Semi-finalists 2000, 2002, 2007.\n* '''[[Kildare Senior Football Championship]]'''s 1962, 2000, 2002, 2006, 2007, 2010, 2013, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/tyrrell-rescues-moores-292134.html|title= Tyrrell rescues Moores|date=20 October 2014|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/gaa/mighty-moorefield-again-kingpins-294124.html|title=Mighty Moorefield again kingpins  |accessdate=27 October 2014 |work=[[The Irish Examiner]] |publisher= |date=27 October 2014}}</ref>, 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hoganstand.com/Kildare/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=276943|title=Kildare SFC final: 13-man Moorefield dig deep to claim title number nine |accessdate=17 October 2017 |work=[[Hogan Stand]] |publisher= |date=15 October 2017}}</ref>, 2018\n* '''[[Kildare Senior Hurling Championship]]''' Winner 1943, 1963, 1991\n* '''[[Kildare Senior Football Championship]]:''' Finalists 1965\n* '''[[Kildare Senior Football League Division 1|Senior Football League]]:''' 1958, 1959, 1960, 1994, 1996, 2008, 2010, 2011,2013, 2015, 2017.\n* '''Kildare Senior B Football Championship''' (6) 1994, 1995, 1997, 2012, 2014, 2016.\n* '''Kildare Intermediate B Football Championship''' (1) 1996\n* '''[[Kildare Intermediate Football Championship]]''' Winners (2) 1937, 1939\n* '''[[Kildare Junior Football Championship]]:''' (2) 1933, 1948\n* '''Kildare Junior B Football Championship:''' (2) 2006. 2007\n* '''Jack Higgins Cup''' 1994, 2006, 2012\n* '''Kildare Junior C Football Championship:''' (3) 1992, 2000, 2001.\n* '''[[Kildare U-21 Football Championship]]''' Winners (4) 1997, 1998, 2000, 2003\n* '''Kildare Minor Football Championship''' Winners (4)1989, 1997, 2003, 2015\n* '''Kildare Intermediate Hurling Championship''' (2) 1998, 2010\n* '''Kildare Junior Hurling Championship''' (6) 1941, 1961, 1979, 1987, 1997 & 2006\n* '''Kildare Junior Football League''' (1) 1936\n* '''Kildare Junior Hurling League''' (1) 1972\n* '''Kildare Senior B Camogie Championship''' (2) 1998, 1999\n* '''Kildare Intermediate Camogie Championship''' (1) 1994\n* '''Kildare Junior Camogie Championship''' (1) 1992\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Curragh Moorefield GAA Club (1984).\n* Kildare GAA: A Centenary History, by [[Eoghan Crory]], CLG Chill Dara, 1984, {{ISBN|0-9509370-0-2}} hb {{ISBN|0-9509370-1-0}} pb\n* Kildare GAA yearbook, 1972, 1974, 1978, 1979, 1980 and 2000\u2013 in sequence especially the Millennium yearbook of 2000\n* Soaring Sliothars: Centenary of Kildare Camogie 1904\u20132004 by Joan O'Flynn Kildare County Camogie Board.\n*Also known as a great sponsor to the castle town donkey derby 1994 where they brought in all their glasses when they were finished \n*in 2018 moorefield received a massive punishment for playing junior b players in a u15 league quarter final and had to give the referee 13 John player blues to keep him quiet \n*moorefield gaa is also well known for destroying the bad turn there just before newbridge golf club as half the players don\u2019t have driving licenses or have a few pints before they head home which is ok if ye smoke benson\n\n==Current Panel==\n* Kevin Murnaghan\n* Daryl Flynn (c)\n* Eddie Ivors\n* Ryan Houlihan\n* Adam Tyrrell\n* Eanna O'Connor - Son of Kerry legend Jack O'Connor\n* Niall Sliotair-Lynch\n* Ronan Sweeney\n* Sean Burke\n* Michael Sammon\n*Tom the landscaper\n*Ian Dunne\n*Brandon Hand\n