{"title_page": "Battle of Cerignola", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict = Battle of Cerignola\n| partof = the [[Second Italian War]]\n| image = Elgrancapitantrasbatalladeceri\u00f1ola.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| caption = ''Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba finds the corpse of Louis d'Armagnac''. [[Federico de Madrazo]], 1835. [[Museo del Prado]].\n| date = 21 April  1503\n| place = [[Cerignola]] (present-day [[Italy]])\n| result = Decisive Spanish victory\n| combatant1 = [[File:Armoiries Espagne Catholique.svg|20px]] [[Catholic Monarchs|Castile and Aragon]]\n| combatant2 = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France|valois}}\n| commander1 = [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba]]<br/>[[Prospero Colonna]]<br/>[[Pedro Navarro]]<br/>[[Fabrizio Colonna]]\n| commander2 = [[Louis d'Armagnac, Duke of Nemours|Duke of Nemours]]{{KIA}}<br/>\nTambi\u00e9n Chandieu{{KIA}}<br/>Yves d'Al\u00e8gre<br/>[[Pierre du Terrail]]\n| strength1 = ~6,300<ref>Mallet, p64 - combined strength deducted from contingents</ref>\n*700 men-at-arms\n*800 light horse\n*1,000 [[arquebusier]]s\n*2.000 [[landsknecht]]s\n*1,000+ other infantry\n20 guns\n| strength2 = ~9,000<ref>Mallet, p64 - combined strength deducted from contingents</ref>\n*650 French [[Gendarme (historical)|gendarmes]]\n*1,100 light horse\n*3,500 Swiss infantry\n*2,500-3,500 French infantry\n40 guns (arrived too late)\n| casualties1 = 100\n| casualties2 = 4,000 killed\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Second Italian War}}\n{{Campaignbox Italian Wars}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Cerignola''' was fought on 21 April   1503, between [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[France|French]] armies, in [[Cerignola]], [[Apulia]] (some 60 km from [[Bari]]).<ref>\nSpencer C. Tucker, ''A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East'', vol. 1, ABC-CLIO, (2009), p. 477.</ref> \nSpanish forces, under [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba]], formed by 6,300 men, including 2,000 [[landsknecht]]e, with more than 1,000 [[arquebusiers]], and 20 cannons, defeated the French who had 9,000 men; mainly heavy [[gendarme]] cavalry and [[Swiss mercenary]] [[Pike (weapon)|pikemen]], with about 40 cannons, and led by [[Louis d'Armagnac, Duke of Nemours]], who was killed.  It was one of the first European battles won by gunpowder weapons, as the assault by Swiss pikemen and French cavalry was shattered by the fire of Spanish arquebusiers behind a ditch.\n\n==Preparations==\nThe [[Second Italian War]] was re-kindled in late 1502, over disagreements on the Treaty of Granada of 11 November 1500. Although it was agreed that Louis XII should assume the [[Kingdom of Naples|throne of Naples]], Louis and the monarchs of Spain soon quarreled over the division of the rest of the spoils.  Soon war broke out again between France and Spain.<ref>Michael Mallett and Christine Shaw, ''The Italian Wars: 1494\u20131559'', p. 61.</ref> \nThe Spanish forces, led by the \"Great Captain\" (''El Gran Capit\u00e1n'')  [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba]] avoided encounter with the enemy at first, hoping to lure the French into complacency.\nAfter a series of skirmishes, the Battle of Cerignola was the first major engagement in this phase of the war, alongside the [[Battle of Seminara (1503)|Battle of Seminara]] (Calabria) fought on the same day.\n\nDe C\u00f3rdoba  had the numerical disadvantage but held the advantage of the terrain, being able to defend fortified high ground against the French assault. \nThe Spanish had occupied the heights of Cerignola, and de C\u00f3rdoba entrenched his soldiers with walls and stakes.\nDe C\u00f3rdoba's infantry was divided into a novel type of units called \"Coronel\u00edas,\" the immediate predecessor of the later [[Tercios]]. They were armed with a mix of pikes, arquebuses and swords. This type of formation had revolutionized the Spanish army, which like the French, had  centred on cavalry well into the 15th century, in the battles of the [[Reconquista]] against the Muslims in Spain.  \nIn front of the hillside, a trench was dug in which the arquebusiers took their positions. The Spanish artillery was placed on top of the hill among the vineyards, having a good view of the entire battlefield. The [[jinetes]], Spanish light cavalry, were placed in front of the rest of the army, while the Spanish heavy cavalry under Prospero Colonna were kept in reserve.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\nDe C\u00f3rdoba's troops faced a professional French army based on the ''Ordonnance'' reforms, relying on the heavily armoured cavalry of the ''Compagnies d'ordonnance'' and mercenary Swiss pikemen. This army also had more artillery than the Spanish, but the French artillery would not arrive in time to take active part in the battle.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==The battle==\nThe battle began with two charges by the French heavy cavalry against the centre of the Spanish army, but these were both dispersed by Spanish heavy artillery and [[arquebus]] fire. The next assault tried to force the right flank, but many of the French cavalrymen fell into the Spanish trench and the attack was then broken by a storm of fire from the Spanish arquebusiers. One of those killed by the arquebus volley was the French commander [[Louis d'Armagnac, Duke of Nemours|Duke of Nemours]], making him probably the first general killed in action by small arms fire.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} . With the Swiss commander, Chandieu, taking charge, the Swiss infantry attacked with the cavalry instead of waiting for the arrival of the French rear guard under Yves d'Al\u00e8gre. At the imminent assault upon the Spanish center the Spanish arquebusiers were withdrawn and the [[Landsknecht]]s sent forward. The Swiss formations, soon joined by the Gascons, were unable to break into the defensive positions. Shot into the flank by the arquebusiers and harassed by the Spanish cavalry, the Swiss and French were driven back, taking heavy casualties including Chandieu.\n\nDe C\u00f3rdoba then called for a counterattack against the now disorganized enemy by both the Spanish infantry and the heavy Spanish cavalry waiting in reserve. Mounted arquebusiers surrounded and routed the remaining French gendarmes, but the Swiss pikeman managed to retreat in a relatively organized fashion.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\nUpon witnessing the defeat of both the gendarmes and the pikemen, d'Al\u00e8gre called for a withdrawal. He was pursued by the victorious Spanish jinetes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\n\"..what happened in the battle of Chirinola {Cerignola}; where an Italian, believing the Spanish were beaten, threw fire in the powder wagons, and the army being confused by such an accident, El Gran Capitan was encouraged saying 'good sign friends, those are the lights of victory' and thus it was.\"  <ref>'Empresas Politicas: O idea de un Principe Politico Christiano representada en cien empreses' Tomo Tres, by Don Diego de Saavedra Faxardo, Madrid 1789, p. 7,8</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe battle resulted in a heavy French defeat with the French reported to have lost around 4,000 men killed,<ref>Mallet, p65</ref> Spanish losses amounting to some 500 men.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref> The French supplies, wagon train and all of the French artillery still in it fell into the hands of the victorious Spanish troops. The end of the battle saw the first time a \"call to prayer\" (toque de oracion) was issued, a practice that was later adopted by most Western armies, when the [[Great Captain]], upon seeing the fields full of French bodies (who, like the Spaniards, were Christian), ordered three long tones to be played and his troops to pray for all the fallen.\n\nAfter the battle the defeated French army retreated to the fortress of [[Gaeta]] north of Naples. De C\u00f3rdoba's forces attempted to storm the fortress, but the attacks all failed. The besieged French were prepared for a long siege and were receiving supplies by sea. Thus unable to take Gaeta and fearing the arrival of possible French reinforcements, De C\u00f3rdoba lifted the siege and retreated to Castellone, some 8 kilometers south of Gaeta.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\nIn retrospect, Cerignola marks the beginning of 140 years of Spanish dominance on European battlefields until the defeat of [[Battle of Rocroi|Rocroi]] in 1643 and also marked the rise of [[pike and shot]] tactics. It is considered to be the first major battle won largely through the use of [[firearm]]s, comparable to what was to occur in Japan seven decades later in the [[Battle of Nagashino]] in 1575.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Batista Gonz\u00e1lez, Juan (2007). ''Espa\u00f1a Estrat\u00e9gica. Guerra y Diplomacia en la Historia de Espa\u00f1a''. S\u00edlex. {{ISBN|978-84-7737-183-0}}\n* Cassidy, Ben. \"Machiavelli and the Ideology of the Offensive: Gunpowder Weapons in the Art of War.\" ''Journal of Military History'' 67#2 (2003): 381-404. [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/journal_of_military_history/v067/67.2cassidy.html online]\n*Losada, Juan Carlos (2006). ''Batallas Decisivas de la Historia de Espa\u00f1a''. Punto de Lectura. {{ISBN|978-84-663-1484-8}}\n*Mallet, Michael and Shaw, Christine. ''The Italian Wars 1494-1559''. Harlow: Pearson Educated Limited (2012) {{ISBN|978-0-582-05758-6}}.\n*Tafi\u0142owski, Piotr (2007). Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559. Zabrze: Inforeditions. {{ISBN|978-83-89943-18-7}}\n\n{{coord|41|16|N|15|54|E|source:eswiki_region:IT_type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1503 in Italy]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Italian Wars|Cerignola 1503]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France|Cerignola 1503]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Spain|Cerignola 1503]]\n[[Category:Battles in Apulia]]\n[[Category:Cerignola|Battle]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1503|Cerignola]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict = Battle of Cerignola\n| partof = the [[Second Italian War]]\n| image = Elgrancapitantrasbatalladeceri\u00f1ola.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| caption = ''Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba finds the corpse of Louis d'Armagnac''. [[Federico de Madrazo]], 1835. [[Museo del Prado]].\n| date = 21 April  1503\n| place = [[Cerignola]] (present-day [[Italy]])\n| result = Decisive Spanish victory\n| combatant1 = [[File:Armoiries Espagne Catholique.svg|20px]] [[Catholic Monarchs|Castile and Aragon]]\n| combatant2 = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France|valois}}\n| commander1 = [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba]]<br/>[[Prospero Colonna]]<br/>[[Pedro Navarro]]<br/>[[Fabrizio Colonna]]\n| commander2 = [[Louis d'Armagnac, Duke of Nemours|Duke of Nemours]]{{KIA}}<br/>\nTambi\u00e9n Chandieu{{KIA}}<br/>Yves d'Al\u00e8gre<br/>[[Pierre du Terrail]]\n| strength1 = ~6,300<ref>Mallet, p64 - combined strength deducted from contingents</ref>\n*700 men-at-arms\n*800 light horse\n*1,000 [[arquebusier]]s\n*2.000 [[landsknecht]]s\n*1,000+ other infantry\n20 guns\n| strength2 = ~9,000<ref>Mallet, p64 - combined strength deducted from contingents</ref>\n*650 French [[Gendarme (historical)|gendarmes]]\n*1,100 light horse\n*3,500 Swiss infantry\n*2,500-3,500 French infantry\n40 guns (arrived too late)\n| casualties1 = 500\n| casualties2 = 4,000 killed\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Second Italian War}}\n{{Campaignbox Italian Wars}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Cerignola''' was fought on 21 April   1503, between [[Spain|Spanish]] and [[France|French]] armies, in [[Cerignola]], [[Apulia]] (some 60 km from [[Bari]]).<ref>\nSpencer C. Tucker, ''A Global Chronology of Conflict: From the Ancient World to the Modern Middle East'', vol. 1, ABC-CLIO, (2009), p. 477.</ref> \nSpanish forces, under [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba]], formed by 6,300 men, including 2,000 [[landsknecht]]e, with more than 1,000 [[arquebusiers]], and 20 cannons, defeated the French who had 9,000 men; mainly heavy [[gendarme]] cavalry and [[Swiss mercenary]] [[Pike (weapon)|pikemen]], with about 40 cannons, and led by [[Louis d'Armagnac, Duke of Nemours]], who was killed.  It was one of the first European battles won by gunpowder weapons, as the assault by Swiss pikemen and French cavalry was shattered by the fire of Spanish arquebusiers behind a ditch.\n\n==Preparations==\nThe [[Second Italian War]] was re-kindled in late 1502, over disagreements on the Treaty of Granada of 11 November 1500. Although it was agreed that Louis XII should assume the [[Kingdom of Naples|throne of Naples]], Louis and the monarchs of Spain soon quarreled over the division of the rest of the spoils.  Soon war broke out again between France and Spain.<ref>Michael Mallett and Christine Shaw, ''The Italian Wars: 1494\u20131559'', p. 61.</ref> \nThe Spanish forces, led by the \"Great Captain\" (''El Gran Capit\u00e1n'')  [[Gonzalo Fern\u00e1ndez de C\u00f3rdoba]] avoided encounter with the enemy at first, hoping to lure the French into complacency.\nAfter a series of skirmishes, the Battle of Cerignola was the first major engagement in this phase of the war, alongside the [[Battle of Seminara (1503)|Battle of Seminara]] (Calabria) fought on the same day.\n\nDe C\u00f3rdoba  had the numerical disadvantage but held the advantage of the terrain, being able to defend fortified high ground against the French assault. \nThe Spanish had occupied the heights of Cerignola, and de C\u00f3rdoba entrenched his soldiers with walls and stakes.\nDe C\u00f3rdoba's infantry was divided into a novel type of units called \"Coronel\u00edas,\" the immediate predecessor of the later [[Tercios]]. They were armed with a mix of pikes, arquebuses and swords. This type of formation had revolutionized the Spanish army, which like the French, had  centred on cavalry well into the 15th century, in the battles of the [[Reconquista]] against the Muslims in Spain.  \nIn front of the hillside, a trench was dug in which the arquebusiers took their positions. The Spanish artillery was placed on top of the hill among the vineyards, having a good view of the entire battlefield. The [[jinetes]], Spanish light cavalry, were placed in front of the rest of the army, while the Spanish heavy cavalry under Prospero Colonna were kept in reserve.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\nDe C\u00f3rdoba's troops faced a professional French army based on the ''Ordonnance'' reforms, relying on the heavily armoured cavalry of the ''Compagnies d'ordonnance'' and mercenary Swiss pikemen. This army also had more artillery than the Spanish, but the French artillery would not arrive in time to take active part in the battle.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==The battle==\nThe battle began with two charges by the French heavy cavalry against the centre of the Spanish army, but these were both dispersed by Spanish heavy artillery and [[arquebus]] fire. The next assault tried to force the right flank, but many of the French cavalrymen fell into the Spanish trench and the attack was then broken by a storm of fire from the Spanish arquebusiers. One of those killed by the arquebus volley was the French commander [[Louis d'Armagnac, Duke of Nemours|Duke of Nemours]], making him probably the first general killed in action by small arms fire.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} . With the Swiss commander, Chandieu, taking charge, the Swiss infantry attacked with the cavalry instead of waiting for the arrival of the French rear guard under Yves d'Al\u00e8gre. At the imminent assault upon the Spanish center the Spanish arquebusiers were withdrawn and the [[Landsknecht]]s sent forward. The Swiss formations, soon joined by the Gascons, were unable to break into the defensive positions. Shot into the flank by the arquebusiers and harassed by the Spanish cavalry, the Swiss and French were driven back, taking heavy casualties including Chandieu.\n\nDe C\u00f3rdoba then called for a counterattack against the now disorganized enemy by both the Spanish infantry and the heavy Spanish cavalry waiting in reserve. Mounted arquebusiers surrounded and routed the remaining French gendarmes, but the Swiss pikeman managed to retreat in a relatively organized fashion.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\nUpon witnessing the defeat of both the gendarmes and the pikemen, d'Al\u00e8gre called for a withdrawal. He was pursued by the victorious Spanish jinetes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\n\"..what happened in the battle of Chirinola {Cerignola}; where an Italian, believing the Spanish were beaten, threw fire in the powder wagons, and the army being confused by such an accident, El Gran Capitan was encouraged saying 'good sign friends, those are the lights of victory' and thus it was.\"  <ref>'Empresas Politicas: O idea de un Principe Politico Christiano representada en cien empreses' Tomo Tres, by Don Diego de Saavedra Faxardo, Madrid 1789, p. 7,8</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe battle resulted in a heavy French defeat with the French reported to have lost around 4,000 men killed,<ref>Mallet, p65</ref> Spanish losses amounting to some 500 men.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref> The French supplies, wagon train and all of the French artillery still in it fell into the hands of the victorious Spanish troops. The end of the battle saw the first time a \"call to prayer\" (toque de oracion) was issued, a practice that was later adopted by most Western armies, when the [[Great Captain]], upon seeing the fields full of French bodies (who, like the Spaniards, were Christian), ordered three long tones to be played and his troops to pray for all the fallen.\n\nAfter the battle the defeated French army retreated to the fortress of [[Gaeta]] north of Naples. De C\u00f3rdoba's forces attempted to storm the fortress, but the attacks all failed. The besieged French were prepared for a long siege and were receiving supplies by sea. Thus unable to take Gaeta and fearing the arrival of possible French reinforcements, De C\u00f3rdoba lifted the siege and retreated to Castellone, some 8 kilometers south of Gaeta.<ref>{{cite book |title=Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559 |last=Tafi\u0142owski |first=Piotr |year=2007 |publisher=Inforeditions |location=Zabrze |isbn=978-83-89943-18-7}}</ref>\n\nIn retrospect, Cerignola marks the beginning of 140 years of Spanish dominance on European battlefields until the defeat of [[Battle of Rocroi|Rocroi]] in 1643 and also marked the rise of [[pike and shot]] tactics. It is considered to be the first major battle won largely through the use of [[firearm]]s, comparable to what was to occur in Japan seven decades later in the [[Battle of Nagashino]] in 1575.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Batista Gonz\u00e1lez, Juan (2007). ''Espa\u00f1a Estrat\u00e9gica. Guerra y Diplomacia en la Historia de Espa\u00f1a''. S\u00edlex. {{ISBN|978-84-7737-183-0}}\n* Cassidy, Ben. \"Machiavelli and the Ideology of the Offensive: Gunpowder Weapons in the Art of War.\" ''Journal of Military History'' 67#2 (2003): 381-404. [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/journal_of_military_history/v067/67.2cassidy.html online]\n*Losada, Juan Carlos (2006). ''Batallas Decisivas de la Historia de Espa\u00f1a''. Punto de Lectura. {{ISBN|978-84-663-1484-8}}\n*Mallet, Michael and Shaw, Christine. ''The Italian Wars 1494-1559''. Harlow: Pearson Educated Limited (2012) {{ISBN|978-0-582-05758-6}}.\n*Tafi\u0142owski, Piotr (2007). Wojny w\u0142oskie 1494-1559. Zabrze: Inforeditions. {{ISBN|978-83-89943-18-7}}\n\n{{coord|41|16|N|15|54|E|source:eswiki_region:IT_type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1503 in Italy]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Italian Wars|Cerignola 1503]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France|Cerignola 1503]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Spain|Cerignola 1503]]\n[[Category:Battles in Apulia]]\n[[Category:Cerignola|Battle]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1503|Cerignola]]\n", "name_user": "87.13.233.74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAftermath)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Cerignola"}
{"title_page": "Karma Paljor", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{ Infobox person\n|name = Karma Paljor\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date= \n|birth_place= [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], [[India]]\n|nationality=[[India]]n\n|education = [[Bangalore University]], [[Xavier Institute of Communication, Mumbai]]\n|occupation = Journalist and news anchor\n|years_active = 2001-present\n|organization =\n|URL =\n}}\n\n'''Karma Paljor''' is an award-winning Indian journalist and television news anchor. His career as a media professional began in 2001 and since then he's been associated with some famous news channel and last channel he was with is [[CNN-News18]].<ref name=\"news18.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news18.com/byline/karma-paljor.html|title=Karma Paljor: Exclusive News Stories by Karma Paljor on Current Affairs, Events at News18|work=news18.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.com/karma-paljor/profile-1914005.html|title=Karma Paljor Profile - Photos, Wallpapers, Videos, News, Movies, Karma Paljor Songs, Pics|work=in.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> He has received several awards for his role as a reporter and for his coverage of natural disasters since then.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAfter attending school in [[Tashi Namgyal Academy]], at his birthplace [[Sikkim]], [[India]], Karma Paljor headed for graduation from [[Bangalore University]] and then post-graduation diploma from Xavier Institute of Communication, [[Mumbai]].\n\n==Career==\n\nKarma started his career with ''[[The Times of India]]'' in [[Mumbai]] and moved to [[CNBC TV18]] in 2001. Apart from covering national and political stories for the channel, Paljor also anchored the breakfast show on [[CNBC TV18]].<ref name=\"news18.com\"/> He won the [[Chevening Scholarship]] for Broadcast journalism in 2004. He joined [[CNN-IBN]] in 2005 as a founding employee and has hosted every possible show on the channel. He specializes in covering aviation and natural disaster. He has planned and executed several award-winning programs like ''Budget Yatra'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-AsYsK_6gQ|title=Budget Yatra 2013: Ground reports on economy from across the country|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ra4rziUwni4|title=Budget Yatra: The 'Make in India' journey of country's aerospace industry|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mSLoYC_j_ss|title=Watch: Budget Yatra in Chattisgarh with Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nFVaNXgfb5I|title=Watch: Budget Yatra with Karma Paljor at 10 pm on CNN-IBN|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jP0dyLVlojU|title=Budget Yatra: Challenges of the tea industry|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''Axe the Tax'', and ''Reporters Project''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JkHnDQB5DmA|title=Reporter's Project: Kota's Coaching Industry, a Cauldron|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/paljor.karma/videos/10154439531842641/|title=Karma Paljor|work=facebook.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CmNZP-MVEmY&t=5s|title=Another IIT aspirant commits suicide in Kota|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> Some of his other shows were ''Cash Crisis Yatra'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kLieBxlGZ74|title=Watch: Cash Crisis Yatra With Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''Interview with Jeff Bezoz'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rKuhxyRrIk8|title=Full Interview -- Jeff Bezos with Karma Paljor -- IBNLive|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''India @9'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hQU77bl_C9Y|title=Watch: India@9 With Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''Big 5 @10''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l2y4ZvMUF8M|title=Watch: Big 5@10 With Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> He also headed the special features team.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\nKarma was awarded the reporter of the year in 2010 by [[Indian Television]] at the News Television Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k10/mar/mar187.php|title=NT Awards honours TV news industry|date=26 March 2010|publisher=Indian Television|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> In 2011, he won the prestigious [[Ramnath Goenka]] Award<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2014/09/cnn-ibn-wins-5-awards-at-ramnath-goenka-excellence-in-journalism-awards | title=CNN-IBN wins 5 awards at Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Awards | date=11 September 2014 | publisher=Best Media Info | accessdate=10 May 2018 }}</ref> for excellence in Journalism in the category for Business and Economic Journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.network18online.com/Awards2.html|title=NETWORK 18|work=network18online.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/cnn-ibn-wins-three-ramnath-goenka-awards-1167900.html|title=IBN wins five Ramnath Goenka Awards|date=23 November 2015|publisher=News 18|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ramnath-goenka-awards-the-storytellers/|title=Ramnath Goenka Awards: The Storytellers|date=14 September 2014|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> His teams coverage of the [[2013 North India floods]] in [[Uttrakhand]], and won the award for the Best National News Coverage in English at the Exchange4media News Broadcasting Awards (ENBA) in 2013.<ref>http://wsds.teriin.org/2015/pdf/speaker/karma.pdf</ref> In 2014, Karma won the ENBA Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uJHOgs2d8nk|title=Network18 bags seven ENBA 2014 awards|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> in the Best Spot News Reporting (English) category for his coverage of [[Cyclone Phailin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/tv/this-award-highlights-how-business-genre-is-becoming-the-mainstreamsanjay-pugalia_58964.html|title=This award highlights how business genre is becoming the mainstream: Sanjay Pugalia|first=|last=www.exchange4media.com|work=exchange4media.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> which won him the [[Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Awards|Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Award]] for on-the-spot reporting in 2014.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite web|url=http://staging.ibnlive.com/byline/karma-paljor.html|title=Karma Paljor: Exclusive News Stories by Karma Paljor on Current Affairs, Events at IBNLive|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate=15 March 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook | paljor.karma |Karma paljor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paljor, Karma}}\n[[Category:Indian male television journalists]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Bangalore University alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Sikkim|journalist]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian television news anchors]]\n[[Category:Indian television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Indian television journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian political journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{ Infobox Person\n|name = Karma Paljor\n|image=\n|caption=\n|birth_date= \n|birth_place= [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], [[India]]\n|nationality=[[India]]n\n|education = [[Bangalore University]], [[Xavier Institute of Communication, Mumbai]]\n|occupation = Journalist and news anchor\n|years_active = 2001-present\n|organization =\n|URL =\n}}\n\n'''Karma Paljor''' is an award-winning Indian journalist and television news anchor. His career as a media professional began in 2001 and since then he's been associated with some famous news channel and last channel he was with is [[CNN-News18]].<ref name=\"news18.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news18.com/byline/karma-paljor.html|title=Karma Paljor: Exclusive News Stories by Karma Paljor on Current Affairs, Events at News18|work=news18.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.com/karma-paljor/profile-1914005.html|title=Karma Paljor Profile - Photos, Wallpapers, Videos, News, Movies, Karma Paljor Songs, Pics|work=in.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> He has received several awards for his role as a reporter and for his coverage of natural disasters since then.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nAfter attending school in [[Tashi Namgyal Academy]], at his birthplace [[Sikkim]], [[India]], Karma Paljor headed for graduation from [[Bangalore University]] and then post-graduation diploma from Xavier Institute of Communication, [[Mumbai]].\n\n==Career==\n\nKarma started his career with ''[[The Times of India]]'' in [[Mumbai]] and moved to [[CNBC TV18]] in 2001. Apart from covering national and political stories for the channel, Paljor also anchored the breakfast show on [[CNBC TV18]].<ref name=\"news18.com\"/> He won the [[Chevening Scholarship]] for Broadcast journalism in 2004. He joined [[CNN-IBN]] in 2005 as a founding employee and has hosted every possible show on the channel. He specializes in covering aviation and natural disaster. He has planned and executed several award-winning programs like ''Budget Yatra'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-AsYsK_6gQ|title=Budget Yatra 2013: Ground reports on economy from across the country|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ra4rziUwni4|title=Budget Yatra: The 'Make in India' journey of country's aerospace industry|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mSLoYC_j_ss|title=Watch: Budget Yatra in Chattisgarh with Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nFVaNXgfb5I|title=Watch: Budget Yatra with Karma Paljor at 10 pm on CNN-IBN|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jP0dyLVlojU|title=Budget Yatra: Challenges of the tea industry|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''Axe the Tax'', and ''Reporters Project''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JkHnDQB5DmA|title=Reporter's Project: Kota's Coaching Industry, a Cauldron|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/paljor.karma/videos/10154439531842641/|title=Karma Paljor|work=facebook.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CmNZP-MVEmY&t=5s|title=Another IIT aspirant commits suicide in Kota|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> Some of his other shows were ''Cash Crisis Yatra'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kLieBxlGZ74|title=Watch: Cash Crisis Yatra With Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''Interview with Jeff Bezoz'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rKuhxyRrIk8|title=Full Interview -- Jeff Bezos with Karma Paljor -- IBNLive|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''India @9'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hQU77bl_C9Y|title=Watch: India@9 With Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ''Big 5 @10''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l2y4ZvMUF8M|title=Watch: Big 5@10 With Karma Paljor|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> He also headed the special features team.\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\nKarma was awarded the reporter of the year in 2010 by [[Indian Television]] at the News Television Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/headlines/y2k10/mar/mar187.php|title=NT Awards honours TV news industry|date=26 March 2010|publisher=Indian Television|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> In 2011, he won the prestigious [[Ramnath Goenka]] Award<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2014/09/cnn-ibn-wins-5-awards-at-ramnath-goenka-excellence-in-journalism-awards | title=CNN-IBN wins 5 awards at Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Awards | date=11 September 2014 | publisher=Best Media Info | accessdate=10 May 2018 }}</ref> for excellence in Journalism in the category for Business and Economic Journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.network18online.com/Awards2.html|title=NETWORK 18|work=network18online.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news18.com/news/india/cnn-ibn-wins-three-ramnath-goenka-awards-1167900.html|title=IBN wins five Ramnath Goenka Awards|date=23 November 2015|publisher=News 18|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/ramnath-goenka-awards-the-storytellers/|title=Ramnath Goenka Awards: The Storytellers|date=14 September 2014|publisher=Indian Express|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref> His teams coverage of the [[2013 North India floods]] in [[Uttrakhand]], and won the award for the Best National News Coverage in English at the Exchange4media News Broadcasting Awards (ENBA) in 2013.<ref>http://wsds.teriin.org/2015/pdf/speaker/karma.pdf</ref> In 2014, Karma won the ENBA Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uJHOgs2d8nk|title=Network18 bags seven ENBA 2014 awards|work=youtube.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> in the Best Spot News Reporting (English) category for his coverage of [[Cyclone Phailin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exchange4media.com/tv/this-award-highlights-how-business-genre-is-becoming-the-mainstreamsanjay-pugalia_58964.html|title=This award highlights how business genre is becoming the mainstream: Sanjay Pugalia|first=|last=www.exchange4media.com|work=exchange4media.com|accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> which won him the [[Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Awards|Ramnath Goenka Excellence in Journalism Award]] for on-the-spot reporting in 2014.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite web|url=http://staging.ibnlive.com/byline/karma-paljor.html|title=Karma Paljor: Exclusive News Stories by Karma Paljor on Current Affairs, Events at IBNLive|publisher=IBN Live|accessdate=15 March 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook | paljor.karma |Karma paljor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paljor, Karma}}\n[[Category:Indian male television journalists]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Bangalore University alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Sikkim|journalist]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian television news anchors]]\n[[Category:Indian television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Indian television journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Indian political journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karma_Paljor"}
{"title_page": "Karl-Heinz Smuda", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2011}}\n{{Notability|bio|date=June 2011}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Karl-Heinz Smuda.jpg|thumb|Karl-Heinz Smuda]]\n'''Karl-Heinz Smuda''' (born January 24, 1961 in [[Eschweiler]]) is a [[German people|German]] radio-[[journalist]], media-expert, [[ghostwriter]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/politik/deutschland/article1798768/Die-Gewinner-der-Plagiats-Affaere.html|title=Die Gewinner der Plagiats-Aff\u00e4re|author=Lars-Marten Nagel|work=abendblatt.de}}</ref> and [[major]] in the [[German Air Force]].\nHe was speaker of the [[MONUSCO|NATO detachment in Siauliai]] and the German detachment of [[EUFOR RD Congo]] in [[Kinshasa]]/ DR Congo.\n\n== Radio career ==\nSmuda was a correspondent for [[Deutschlandradio]], [[Germany]]\u00b4s national [[radio]] public broadcast system, and head of a radio station in the former East German country of [[Brandenburg]]. After the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], he worked as a reporter in [[Leipzig]], and became known for his reports on the lives of the [[citizen]]s of [[East Germany]]. For the past 30 years, Smuda has worked for various radio stations in Germany, as well as making a series of [[Broadcasting|broadcasts]] from the [[United States]] concerning [[politics]] and [[culture]] in the [[Oregon]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Massachusetts]], [[California]] and [[North Carolina]]. He worked as an [[editing|editor]] in the German department of [[Radio Vatican]] in 1980 and 1981. Smuda has made 12000 reports from Germany and all over the world. He is a lecturer at the [[University of Wuppertal]] and Cottbus, trainer in the Academy for communication and information of German Air Force in Strauberg, near Berlin.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n== Background ==\nSmuda received a [[scholarship]] for his work in [[children's television]] in [[Manila]]. He worked as a [[reporter]] in the crisis areas of [[East Timor]] and [[Kosovo]]. He has studied [[social science]]. He currently resides in [[Wilmersdorf]] area of West-[[Berlin]]. Smuda has also worked as a speaker for the German detachment of [[NATO]] [[Baltic Air Policing]] in [[\u0160iauliai]] in [[Lithuania]]. Afterwards, he worked in the Operation Headquarter of EU in Potsdam for preparation Europe's engagement during the election in the Democratic Republic Congo (PR) and was Press Information Officer (PIO/ Major OF3) in Kinshasa. He was chief-editor of the newspaper \"ECHO\" during the multinational exercise ELITE 2006 for 16 countries.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smuda, Karl-Heinz}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Eschweiler]]\n[[Category:German journalists]]\n[[Category:German male journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Wuppertal faculty]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2011}}\n{{Notability|bio|date=June 2011}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Karl-Heinz Smuda.jpg|thumb|Karl-Heinz Smuda]]\n'''Karl-Heinz Smuda''' (born January 24, 1961 in [[Eschweiler]]) is a [[German people|German]] radio-[[journalist]], media-expert, [[ghostwriter]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abendblatt.de/politik/deutschland/article1798768/Die-Gewinner-der-Plagiats-Affaere.html|title=Die Gewinner der Plagiats-Aff\u00e4re|author=Lars-Marten Nagel|work=abendblatt.de}}</ref> and [[major]] in the [[German Air Force]].\nHe was speaker of the [[MONUSCO|NATO detachment in Siauliai]] and the German detachment of [[EUFOR RD Congo]] in [[Kinshasa]]/ DR Congo.\n\n== Radio career ==\nSmuda was a correspondent for [[Deutschlandradio]], [[Germany]]\u00b4s national [[radio]] public broadcast system, and head of a radio station in the former East German country of [[Brandenburg]]. After the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]], he worked as a reporter in [[Leipzig]], and became known for his reports on the lives of the [[citizen]]s of [[East Germany]]. For the past 30 years, Smuda has worked for various radio stations in Germany, as well as making a series of [[Broadcasting|broadcasts]] from the [[United States]] concerning [[politics]] and [[culture]] in the [[Oregon]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Massachusetts]], [[California]] and [[North Carolina]]. He worked as an [[editing|editor]] in the German department of [[Radio Vatican]] in 1980 and 1981. Smuda has made 12000 reports from Germany and all over the world. He is a lecturer at the [[University of Wuppertal]] and Cottbus, trainer in the Academy for communication and information of German Air Force in Strauberg, near Berlin.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n== Background ==\nSmuda received a [[scholarship]] for his work in [[children's television]] in [[Manila]]. He worked as a [[reporter]] in the crisis areas of [[East Timor]] and [[Kosovo]]. He has studied [[social science]]. He currently resides in [[Wilmersdorf]] area of West-[[Berlin]]. Smuda has also worked as a speaker for the German detachment of [[NATO]] [[Baltic Air Policing]] in [[\u0160iauliai]] in [[Lithuania]]. Afterwards, he worked in the Operation Headquarter of EU in Potsdam for preparation Europe's engagement during the election in the Democratic Republic Congo (PR) and was Press Information Officer (PIO/ Major OF3) in Kinshasa. He was chief-editor of the newspaper \"ECHO\" during the multinational exercise ELITE 2006 for 16 countries.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smuda, Karl-Heinz}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Eschweiler]]\n[[Category:German journalists]]\n[[Category:German male journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Wuppertal faculty]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", 